-Victoria. Welcome to Boulder. -Very nice to meet you.

58:55.866 --> 58:57.617
-Thank you. -Very nice meeting you.

58:57.659 --> 59:00.537
So you live in California? You're based in California?

59:00.578 --> 59:01.997
Yeah, I'm at Cal Tech.

59:02.039 --> 59:03.707
-Cal Tech? -In Pasadena, yes.

59:03.748 --> 59:05.292
Oh, I didn't know!

59:05.334 --> 59:07.044
You didn't tell me they're from Cal Tech.

59:09.296 --> 59:11.173
[Jun] As we know, time and space

59:11.215 --> 59:13.175
is fundamentally connected.

59:16.387 --> 59:18.555
We are really exploring the frontiers

59:18.596 --> 59:21.725
of quantum physics and quantum technology.

59:26.522 --> 59:28.940
Have you watched the movie called<i> Interstellar?</i>

59:28.982 --> 59:31.485
-I haven't seen<i> Interstellar.</i> -It was a great movie.

59:31.527 --> 59:34.821
These astronauts went in near the black hole.

59:34.863 --> 59:36.490
When he came back,

59:36.532 --> 59:37.908
the daughter was much older than him.

59:37.949 --> 59:39.410
Yeah.

59:39.451 --> 59:40.994
You'll see some of that in our lab tomorrow.

59:41.036 --> 59:42.454
-Great! -It's not science fiction.

59:42.496 --> 59:45.249
You'll actually see clocks slow down

59:45.290 --> 59:48.168
as you get closer to the center of the earth.

59:48.210 --> 59:49.669
No kidding?

59:49.711 --> 59:51.713
So, that's...

59:51.755 --> 59:53.590
It's the relativity effect that Einstein

59:53.631 --> 59:55.592
postulated a hundred years ago.

59:55.633 --> 59:57.428
It's called general relativity,

59:57.469 --> 59:59.471
that time is all relative,

59:59.513 --> 1:00:02.224
and when you have heavy mass,

1:00:02.266 --> 1:00:04.435
it's going to warp the space-time around you.

1:00:04.476 --> 1:00:06.311
-Yeah. -And time is going

1:00:04.476 --> 1:00:06.311
to be different.

1:00:06.353 --> 1:00:08.688
And we can test that. If you raise your watch

1:00:08.730 --> 1:00:14.778
by a couple of centimeters, the time speeds up...

1:00:14.819 --> 1:00:16.696
at a very small level. Only modern atomic clocks

1:00:16.738 --> 1:00:18.615
now can detect those.

1:00:18.656 --> 1:00:21.368
Okay, so you're saying if you move your watch a few...

1:00:21.410 --> 1:00:23.912
centimeters distance...

1:00:23.954 --> 1:00:26.206
-You can tell the difference. Yeah.

1:00:23.954 --> 1:00:26.206
-You detect change?

1:00:26.248 --> 1:00:28.250
And at what level... Like, how many...

1:00:28.292 --> 1:00:30.294
How many decimal points

1:00:30.335 --> 1:00:31.503
do we need to go out?

1:00:31.545 --> 1:00:33.213
-It's 10 to the 18th. -Okay.

1:00:33.255 --> 1:00:35.006
Yeah.

1:00:35.048 --> 1:00:38.093
The clock is already a quantum sensor.

1:00:38.135 --> 1:00:40.512
I actually like to call it a sensor.

1:00:40.554 --> 1:00:43.140
It's something we use to measure.

1:00:48.479 --> 1:00:51.773
Thanks everybody for showing up.

1:00:51.815 --> 1:00:54.067
I would like to introduce you to Victoria.

1:00:54.109 --> 1:00:56.736
She's a professor at Cal Tech.

1:00:56.778 --> 1:00:58.614
The thing that impressed me most is that she dived down

1:00:58.655 --> 1:01:00.740
5,000 meters to the bottom of the ocean

1:01:00.782 --> 1:01:02.909
and studied ecosystems.

1:01:02.951 --> 1:01:05.203
I'm part of the Geological and Planetary Science

1:01:05.245 --> 1:01:06.788
division at Cal Tech.

1:01:06.830 --> 1:01:08.582
But, today... I think we

1:01:08.624 --> 1:01:11.960
I think we want to give her a treat.

1:01:12.002 --> 1:01:14.338
To kind of participate in a group discussion

1:01:14.379 --> 1:01:16.256
that's very technical on the physics side of

1:01:16.298 --> 1:01:18.800
making clocks and understanding strontium atoms.

1:01:18.842 --> 1:01:21.595
Go easy with the descriptions.

1:01:21.637 --> 1:01:23.680
When things get really, really cold,

1:01:23.721 --> 1:01:25.557
The quantum mechanics mayor

1:01:25.599 --> 1:01:27.267
the fact that an atom is on a particle.

1:01:27.309 --> 1:01:29.436
But a wave begins to matter.

1:01:29.478 --> 1:01:31.688
We want a very particular frequency.

1:01:31.729 --> 1:01:33.815
We want that to be as precise as possible.

1:01:33.857 --> 1:01:36.443
For this upcoming clock comparison, we're going to

1:01:33.857 --> 1:01:36.443
compare

1:01:36.485 --> 1:01:37.861
one of these strontium optical lattice blocks

1:01:37.902 --> 1:01:39.488
to the terbium optical lattice blocks.

1:01:39.530 --> 1:01:42.157
This is a boring image, and that's good.

1:01:42.199 --> 1:01:44.951
We want these images to be as boring as possible.

1:01:44.993 --> 1:01:47.162
So hundreds of terahertz as opposed to

1:01:47.204 --> 1:01:48.580
tens of gigahertz frequencies.

1:01:48.622 --> 1:01:50.207
Just to make sure I understand...

1:01:50.248 --> 1:01:53.502
So you have your ground state,

1:01:53.544 --> 1:01:56.796
then you shine... light at a certain frequency,

1:01:56.838 --> 1:01:58.173
and then you look at it again?

1:01:58.215 --> 1:02:00.008
-Yes. -And then, you're seeing,

1:02:00.050 --> 1:02:02.594
how many of those atoms then are at the excited state

1:02:02.636 --> 1:02:04.555
and what's their spatial distribution?

1:02:04.596 --> 1:02:07.015
Isn't that amazing? Isn't it amazing?

1:02:07.057 --> 1:02:09.601
She totally understood the clock measurements.

1:02:14.105 --> 1:02:16.400
Welcome to our lab.

1:02:16.441 --> 1:02:18.776
It'll be different from the ocean field.

1:02:18.818 --> 1:02:20.362
Yeah. Yeah.

1:02:20.404 --> 1:02:22.947
So, it will look a bit random

1:02:22.989 --> 1:02:24.449
with lots of ancient things.

1:02:24.491 --> 1:02:26.451
But believe me, all the cables there...

1:02:26.493 --> 1:02:28.870
There is a purpose for all these cables.

1:02:31.873 --> 1:02:34.167
I'll take you right into

1:02:34.209 --> 1:02:36.878
this particular system right here.

1:02:36.920 --> 1:02:40.131
If you look just to the right side of this lens,

1:02:40.173 --> 1:02:42.467
into the vacuum chamber,

1:02:42.509 --> 1:02:44.386
do you see that little ball of blue light?

1:02:44.428 --> 1:02:47.180
-Yes! -These are 10 million atoms

1:02:47.222 --> 1:02:49.974
of strontium fluorescing under this light.

1:02:50.016 --> 1:02:52.227
And you can see, it's stationary.

1:02:52.269 --> 1:02:53.645
There's nothing else in there.

1:02:53.687 --> 1:02:55.939
It's a vacuum chamber and a light.

1:02:55.980 --> 1:02:59.025
Those atoms provide this swing

1:02:59.067 --> 1:03:01.361
of the pendulum when you open a grandfather clock,

1:03:01.403 --> 1:03:03.363
that's the first thing you see,

1:03:03.405 --> 1:03:05.532
that there's something swinging back and forth, a pendulum.

1:03:05.574 --> 1:03:07.033
That's your pendulum right there.

1:03:07.075 --> 1:03:08.952
The blue ball, which is oscillating

1:03:08.993 --> 1:03:11.788
at about a million billion cycles per second.

1:03:16.668 --> 1:03:18.545
This is actually the world's

1:03:18.587 --> 1:03:21.423
most accurate atomic clock that's ever built.

1:03:21.465 --> 1:03:24.509
It's called a strontium optical lattice clock.

1:03:24.551 --> 1:03:27.471
What it means, over the entire age of the universe,

1:03:27.512 --> 1:03:30.432
it would lose less than one second of the time.

1:03:30.474 --> 1:03:32.225
The fact that we have this open right now

1:03:32.267 --> 1:03:34.311
and we are filming it...

1:03:34.352 --> 1:03:36.020
The clock won't work very well right now

1:03:36.062 --> 1:03:37.522
because we are all here.

1:03:37.564 --> 1:03:39.274
We are warm bodies.

1:03:39.316 --> 1:03:41.610
We have a lot of temperature gradient.

1:03:41.652 --> 1:03:43.487
It's probably changing these mirrors by

1:03:43.528 --> 1:03:45.822
just such a small, tiny amount

1:03:45.863 --> 1:03:48.241
that can cause a little bit of a misalignment.

1:03:51.286 --> 1:03:53.830
[Victoria] The fact that they can control atoms

1:03:53.871 --> 1:03:56.166
under super-cooled conditions, but we're looking at it

1:03:56.207 --> 1:03:58.168
like it's just hanging like a magic ball

1:03:58.209 --> 1:04:01.254
of light, it's wild.

1:04:05.300 --> 1:04:08.804
So Chris and I are academic brothers.

1:04:08.845 --> 1:04:11.431
Yes, we've known each other for

1:04:11.473 --> 1:04:13.433
more than 20... about 25 years, I guess.

1:04:20.816 --> 1:04:22.359
So this laboratory has one of our

1:04:22.400 --> 1:04:24.528
optical atomic clocks in it.

1:04:24.569 --> 1:04:26.613
Atomic clocks play, actually, a very important role,

1:04:26.655 --> 1:04:28.699
even in driving your car in the sense that

1:04:28.740 --> 1:04:31.451
the whole GPS constellation is full of atomic clocks.

1:04:31.493 --> 1:04:33.286
How many people hit...

1:04:33.328 --> 1:04:36.206
and just use a data server

1:04:36.247 --> 1:04:38.249
to synchronize their clock?

1:04:38.291 --> 1:04:40.627
We get something like 20 billion hits a day.

1:04:40.669 --> 1:04:42.796
-20 billion? -Billion! Which is...

1:04:42.838 --> 1:04:45.256
I mean, Google, I think, gets something like 7 billion hits.

1:04:45.298 --> 1:04:47.258
Now granted, Google's requests are a little more complicated

1:04:47.300 --> 1:04:49.052
than "What time is it?"

1:04:49.093 --> 1:04:51.805
Computers all around the world are constantly hitting

1:04:51.847 --> 1:04:54.015
this to re-clock, asking for what time it is.

1:04:55.975 --> 1:04:57.935
So what we have here is

1:04:57.977 --> 1:04:59.396
the calcium thermal beam clock.

1:04:59.437 --> 1:05:01.565
By far the best part is when the light

1:05:01.606 --> 1:05:04.317
is hitting the atoms, and the atoms are telling you stuff.

1:05:04.359 --> 1:05:06.444
-Communicating. -This process just...

1:05:06.486 --> 1:05:07.738
It really is infectious.

1:05:07.779 --> 1:05:09.489
You can tell Chris is very passionate.

1:05:09.531 --> 1:05:12.325
He's talking about atoms and humanizing them.

1:05:12.367 --> 1:05:15.328
He's talking about he and she, and she is communicating back.

1:05:15.370 --> 1:05:18.331
Once you get into this very intimate game of

1:05:18.373 --> 1:05:20.667
getting information, you do feel like you're talking to something

1:05:20.709 --> 1:05:23.086
almost intelligent, but... But, it's...

1:05:23.127 --> 1:05:25.255
It's just something you can't help because you get

1:05:25.296 --> 1:05:27.841
such an intimate working relationship with them.

1:05:29.300 --> 1:05:31.177
Some people say, what do you need

1:05:31.219 --> 1:05:33.388
another digit on your atomic clock for?

1:05:33.430 --> 1:05:35.599
I get asked that question all the time.

1:05:35.640 --> 1:05:38.268
And the answer is that time, sort of paradoxically,

1:05:38.309 --> 1:05:40.771
is a quantity that we don't understand

1:05:40.812 --> 1:05:42.689
philosophically very well at all. I mean...

1:05:42.731 --> 1:05:45.692
no one really has a great sense of what time really is.

1:05:45.734 --> 1:05:47.402
But we can measure it,

1:05:47.444 --> 1:05:49.279
5,6,7 orders of magnitude better

1:05:49.320 --> 1:05:51.072
than any other physical quantity.

1:05:51.114 --> 1:05:53.700
We have not really seen any fundamental limits

1:05:53.742 --> 1:05:56.578
-to...to clocks. -What you can't do yet, yeah.

1:05:56.620 --> 1:05:58.455
-Right, exactly. -You can't just say, "Oh!

1:05:58.496 --> 1:05:59.915
We'll never get better than that."

1:05:59.956 --> 1:06:01.499
We haven't really seen that.

1:06:16.681 --> 1:06:18.516
[Jun] To build the very best clock,

1:06:18.558 --> 1:06:20.685
if you say, I raise my clock

1:06:20.727 --> 1:06:22.729
from the ground up,

1:06:22.771 --> 1:06:25.273
and the time speeds up a little bit.

1:06:25.315 --> 1:06:27.191
As you move towards the mountain,

1:06:27.233 --> 1:06:29.402
time will slow down.

1:06:29.444 --> 1:06:31.112
[Victoria] Just like going to the center of the earth.

1:06:31.154 --> 1:06:32.697
You're moving towards a bigger mass.

1:06:32.739 --> 1:06:34.783
Exactly! It's the big mass that matters.

1:06:34.825 --> 1:06:37.619
Could you by following how much time

1:06:37.661 --> 1:06:39.871
slows back out the mass?

1:06:39.913 --> 1:06:41.957
-That it's? -Yes.

1:06:41.998 --> 1:06:45.126
Say we place a clock around Yellowstone National Park,

1:06:45.168 --> 1:06:47.754
and see whether there will be a danger,

1:06:47.796 --> 1:06:50.465
where there's too much mass starting to amass underneath.

1:06:50.507 --> 1:06:52.049
Eventually, it's going to erupt.

1:06:52.091 --> 1:06:54.928
It would be great to have that warning.

1:06:54.970 --> 1:06:56.972
The clock will tell you that.

1:07:05.480 --> 1:07:08.441
Measurement really is at the heart of modern science.

1:07:08.483 --> 1:07:12.612
Everything is based on measurement.

1:07:12.654 --> 1:07:15.866
There's still certainly many mysteries out there.

1:07:15.907 --> 1:07:17.951
Science has always gone this way...

1:07:17.993 --> 1:07:20.495
You use what you have understood.

1:07:20.537 --> 1:07:22.789
You build better instrumentation and you go out there.

1:07:22.831 --> 1:07:25.166
You measure, you find things

1:07:25.208 --> 1:07:27.711
which is different from what you predict.

1:07:27.752 --> 1:07:29.838
You have heard the terms of

1:07:29.880 --> 1:07:31.840
dark matter, dark energy.

1:07:31.882 --> 1:07:33.633
There's something beyond.

1:07:33.675 --> 1:07:36.135
We don't know yet what that is.

1:07:36.177 --> 1:07:38.013
There are explosions happening when the black holes merge.

1:07:39.931 --> 1:07:41.641
There's gravitational waves being emitted

1:07:41.683 --> 1:07:43.267
throughout the universe.

1:07:43.309 --> 1:07:44.811
Maybe we can even hear the echo

1:07:44.853 --> 1:07:47.271
of the Big Bang

1:07:47.313 --> 1:07:49.816
coming back from the edge of the universe.

1:07:51.234 --> 1:07:54.153
As you build the clock to the 19s, 20s digits,

1:07:54.195 --> 1:07:56.614
what are we going to see?

1:08:22.933 --> 1:08:25.769
[man] I guess I was always interested in the brain.

1:08:27.353 --> 1:08:30.607
It still, at the end of the day, might prove to be

1:08:30.648 --> 1:08:34.235
this mystery that we can't understand.

