We may still just lack

1:09:32.168 --> 1:09:34.211
the sufficient technology, yeah.

1:09:34.253 --> 1:09:37.298
-And it's... -You hit a resonance there

1:09:37.340 --> 1:09:39.717
when you said it's all about measurement in science.

1:09:39.759 --> 1:09:42.386
I have colleagues who build magnetometers,

1:09:42.428 --> 1:09:44.263
which can be implemented.

1:09:44.305 --> 1:09:47.100
-Oh really? -Around brains to

1:09:44.305 --> 1:09:47.100
do brain imaging.

1:09:47.142 --> 1:09:48.852
So, we develop instrumentation

1:09:48.893 --> 1:09:50.812
that hopefully can be useful for you guys.

1:09:50.854 --> 1:09:52.939
Excellent! Bring any with you?

1:09:52.981 --> 1:09:55.191
No, I didn't.

1:09:58.486 --> 1:10:00.321
That's the other important part...

1:10:00.363 --> 1:10:03.240
-Welcome to the UK, of course. -Thank you very much, yeah.

1:10:03.282 --> 1:10:04.826
See some countryside, have a drink.

1:10:07.162 --> 1:10:08.705
And a...

1:10:08.746 --> 1:10:10.623
-Do you just want... -Just a glass of water.

1:10:10.665 --> 1:10:12.208
Yeah, thank you.

1:10:12.249 --> 1:10:15.753
I'm interested about our experience

1:10:15.795 --> 1:10:17.839
of what you might call psychological time.

1:10:17.881 --> 1:10:20.257
-Speeding up as we get older. -It can be very subjective.

1:10:20.299 --> 1:10:22.301
Part of the puzzle is that

1:10:22.343 --> 1:10:24.888
we don't have time detectors

1:10:24.929 --> 1:10:27.015
in in our brains.

1:10:27.057 --> 1:10:28.933
I think it's one of the longstanding...

1:10:28.975 --> 1:10:30.351
challenges

1:10:30.393 --> 1:10:32.228
is to figure out

1:10:32.269 --> 1:10:34.898
how the brain constructs the experience of time

1:10:34.939 --> 1:10:37.358
given that it's got no time sensors.

1:10:37.400 --> 1:10:39.903
What's it based on?

1:10:39.944 --> 1:10:42.697
I'll be very interested to see what you think of this.

1:10:42.739 --> 1:10:44.824
-And this is... -Warrick Roseboom.

1:10:44.866 --> 1:10:46.826
Hi, I'm Jun. Nice to meet you.

1:10:46.868 --> 1:10:48.619
He really knows much more about time than I do.

1:10:48.661 --> 1:10:50.830
This will be the first time

1:10:50.872 --> 1:10:52.916
we've run a person as subject

1:10:52.957 --> 1:10:55.793
on this particular experiment.

1:10:55.835 --> 1:10:57.795
What's going to happen is he's going to watch this video.

1:10:57.837 --> 1:11:00.715
That will go for some duration.

1:11:00.757 --> 1:11:03.218
If you look through the, through the magnet ball.

1:11:03.259 --> 1:11:05.929
-Yes. -At the back, there's a screen.

1:11:05.970 --> 1:11:08.514
It's showing the same thing you see here.

1:11:08.556 --> 1:11:10.516
And then after that video finishes, this will come up.

1:11:10.558 --> 1:11:12.977
You just move the joystick

1:11:13.019 --> 1:11:15.438
until the number on the scale represents

1:11:15.479 --> 1:11:17.815
-how long you felt it went for. -Okay.

1:11:25.740 --> 1:11:27.742
[Anil] We are going to be recording

1:11:27.784 --> 1:11:30.578
what his brain is doing.

1:11:30.620 --> 1:11:32.413
The reason we're doing this is...

1:11:32.455 --> 1:11:34.331
It's obviously nice to see inside somebody's brain

1:11:34.373 --> 1:11:36.542
but we are trying to see

1:11:36.584 --> 1:11:39.003
how well our model of time perception

1:11:39.045 --> 1:11:41.965
matches to what Jun's brain is doing.

1:11:42.006 --> 1:11:44.592
[machine beeping]

1:11:45.426 --> 1:11:47.553
Quite loud.

1:11:47.595 --> 1:11:50.265
Is that okay if we start the experiment now, Jun?

1:11:50.306 --> 1:11:52.058
-Are you ready? -Yes, I'm ready.

1:11:52.100 --> 1:11:54.185
Okay.

1:11:54.227 --> 1:11:56.980
So now, we're waiting for the first video to come up.

1:11:59.482 --> 1:12:02.110
Pretty stable scene. There's not much going on.

1:12:02.152 --> 1:12:04.028
This is one of our office spaces

1:12:04.070 --> 1:12:05.905
in the other building.

1:12:05.947 --> 1:12:07.490
It's just lots of people thinking very hard,

1:12:07.531 --> 1:12:09.200
not much actual visual stuff happening.

1:12:09.242 --> 1:12:11.619
Good, you can see he's making a response.

1:12:11.661 --> 1:12:14.247
Let's see how long he thought that was.

1:12:32.515 --> 1:12:33.766
How well did you think you did?

1:12:33.808 --> 1:12:35.893
I felt...

1:12:35.935 --> 1:12:39.981
I felt I was doing well.

1:12:40.023 --> 1:12:42.441
We think you may not have done quite so well.

1:12:42.483 --> 1:12:43.985
Okay, that's good. Yeah.

1:12:44.027 --> 1:12:45.695
The first few videos, it seemed that...

1:12:45.736 --> 1:12:47.155
-I was way off? -You were.

1:12:47.197 --> 1:12:49.365
It looked like you were overestimating.

1:12:49.406 --> 1:12:51.450
-Okay. -Quite, quite a lot.

1:12:51.492 --> 1:12:53.410
Which is interesting, for somebody who's built

1:12:53.452 --> 1:12:56.331
the world's most accurate clock.

1:12:56.372 --> 1:12:57.540
That is my brain, huh?

1:12:57.581 --> 1:12:59.625
That. That's your brain.

1:12:59.667 --> 1:13:02.461
Do you recognize any bits of your brain there?

1:13:02.503 --> 1:13:04.380
I don't.

1:13:04.421 --> 1:13:06.966
This is my first time looking at my brain.

1:13:07.008 --> 1:13:10.970
-I've never done this scan before.

1:13:07.008 --> 1:13:10.970
-Okay.

1:13:11.012 --> 1:13:14.390
[Anil] We don't have time sensors in the brain.

1:13:14.431 --> 1:13:17.476
Time has to be a construction.

1:13:18.895 --> 1:13:21.105
One idea is that our experience

1:13:21.147 --> 1:13:23.733
of time comes about through

1:13:23.774 --> 1:13:26.361
how things change in our visual perception.

1:13:26.402 --> 1:13:29.155
There's lots of change, and maybe

1:13:29.197 --> 1:13:32.158
our durations will seem longer.

1:13:32.200 --> 1:13:33.910
If nothing changes,

1:13:33.951 --> 1:13:36.537
our experience of time will be really impoverished.

1:13:36.579 --> 1:13:40.875
We're trying to close the loop and come up with

1:13:40.917 --> 1:13:43.586
a unified explanation of human time perception.

1:13:46.214 --> 1:13:48.632
But it goes deeper than that.

1:13:51.010 --> 1:13:52.720
If you want to understand

1:13:52.762 --> 1:13:55.932
the relationship between brains and consciousness,

1:13:55.973 --> 1:13:58.475
in my lab we've got mathematicians

1:13:58.517 --> 1:14:01.520
and physicists and virtual reality engineers.

1:14:01.562 --> 1:14:04.774
[Jun] Oh, now it looks very strange!

1:14:04.815 --> 1:14:07.735
For a second, this didn't turn into animals.

1:14:07.777 --> 1:14:10.113
I've never seen things like that before.

1:14:11.239 --> 1:14:13.616
[Anil] One of the things that I've

1:14:13.657 --> 1:14:15.243
really tried to cultivate

1:14:15.285 --> 1:14:17.370
is a very interdisciplinary approach

1:14:17.412 --> 1:14:19.622
to get at this problem, this basic problem,

1:14:19.663 --> 1:14:21.540
of how consciousness happens.

1:14:30.716 --> 1:14:33.219
What a beautiful place.

1:14:34.553 --> 1:14:36.306
There's this perspective,

1:14:36.347 --> 1:14:38.349
I think it's a pretty poor argument,

1:14:38.391 --> 1:14:40.017
but it's called Mysterianism.

1:14:40.059 --> 1:14:41.560
So there's the idea that

1:14:41.602 --> 1:14:44.021
even if we have arbitrarily fast computers

1:14:44.063 --> 1:14:45.648
and all the technology that we want,

1:14:45.689 --> 1:14:47.691
there will still be some things

1:14:47.733 --> 1:14:50.611
that will forever defy our understanding,

1:14:50.653 --> 1:14:51.946
because we humans are

1:14:51.988 --> 1:14:54.324
cognitively limited in some way.

1:14:54.365 --> 1:14:57.118
However much we magnify our cognitive abilities

1:14:57.160 --> 1:15:00.288
through technology, there must be things

1:15:00.330 --> 1:15:02.206
that we cannot understand

1:15:02.248 --> 1:15:04.083
however much help we have.

1:15:04.125 --> 1:15:05.835
In the same way that if you're a frog,

1:15:05.876 --> 1:15:07.795
however much help you give the frog,

1:15:07.837 --> 1:15:10.256
it's not going to understand quantum mechanics.

1:15:10.298 --> 1:15:11.841
It's still a frog.

1:15:11.882 --> 1:15:13.801
So there might be an equivalent for us.

1:15:13.843 --> 1:15:16.346
On the other hand, the history of science

1:15:16.387 --> 1:15:18.264
has been quite astounding.

1:15:18.306 --> 1:15:20.391
There have been things that people would've thought

1:15:20.433 --> 1:15:21.684
completely beyond our understanding.

1:15:21.725 --> 1:15:23.769
We can and we have.

1:15:27.357 --> 1:15:29.692
[Jun] Though I have only known Anil for two days,

1:15:29.733 --> 1:15:32.778
I feel he's a... a true scientist.

1:15:32.820 --> 1:15:35.448
It's really appealing to me that

1:15:35.490 --> 1:15:37.158
we can speak from, coming from

1:15:37.200 --> 1:15:38.993
very different scientific disciplines.

1:15:39.035 --> 1:15:40.744
And yet, we speak a common language.

1:15:40.786 --> 1:15:42.830
It's been a really pleasure to spend time with Jun.

1:15:42.872 --> 1:15:45.624
He's a... such a nice man,

1:15:45.666 --> 1:15:47.668
in addition to being a brilliant scientist.

1:15:47.710 --> 1:15:51.214
And you never know where...

1:15:51.255 --> 1:15:53.966
where these conversations go. [Jun] Step by step, we can ask

1:15:54.008 --> 1:15:56.719
deeper, deeper questions,

1:15:56.760 --> 1:15:59.638
so we know we are making progress.

1:15:59.680 --> 1:16:01.598
But how long it's going to get there?

1:16:01.640 --> 1:16:03.059
If you asked me that question,

1:16:03.100 --> 1:16:04.977
I couldn't really make that prediction

1:16:05.019 --> 1:16:08.105
because discovery itself is a very uncertain process.

1:16:10.024 --> 1:16:12.402
It's actually exciting that there remains to be

1:16:12.443 --> 1:16:14.862
very many mysteries out there

1:16:14.904 --> 1:16:17.240
that are waiting for us to discover.

1:16:19.200 --> 1:16:22.119
[Anil] The history of science is full of examples

1:16:22.161 --> 1:16:24.955
where an understanding has been developed

1:16:24.997 --> 1:16:27.333
for something that seemed previously entirely mysterious.

1:16:27.375 --> 1:16:29.043
And the reason it can do that

1:16:29.085 --> 1:16:31.170
is because it's a cumulative enterprise.

1:16:31.212 --> 1:16:33.005
You don't start from scratch.

1:16:33.047 --> 1:16:35.716
Every time in science, you're building on

1:16:35.758 --> 1:16:38.052
a whole tradition, not only of knowledge

1:16:38.094 --> 1:16:40.637
but also of methods and techniques.

1:16:59.490 --> 1:17:02.743
[woman] The mind is all the time processing all this stuff

1:17:02.785 --> 1:17:05.621
that it shouldn't have the capacity to process.

1:17:07.290 --> 1:17:09.833
One of these things is our experiences.

1:17:20.719 --> 1:17:22.472
How do we make sense of an event?

1:17:22.513 --> 1:17:24.557
Like you're, you're...

1:17:24.599 --> 1:17:26.392
Folks are watching this movie, and at the end of this movie,

1:17:26.434 --> 1:17:28.727
someone might be like, "Hey, how was<i> The Most Unknown?</i>

1:17:28.769 --> 1:17:30.980
How was that film?" And people will have an answer.

1:17:31.021 --> 1:17:32.565
How did they do that?

1:17:32.607 --> 1:17:34.358
Is your mind keeping a running ticker

1:17:34.400 --> 1:17:35.776
of how good the movie is?

1:17:35.818 --> 1:17:37.069
They see the monkey parts,

1:17:37.111 --> 1:17:38.488
that was really good and it goes up.

1:17:38.529 --> 1:17:40.281
But, this physics... boring.

1:17:40.323 --> 1:17:42.408
But, so it turns out that

1:17:42.450 --> 1:17:45.161
when psychologists look at that, people simplify it.

1:17:45.202 --> 1:17:47.746
So people only take into account two points:

1:17:47.788 --> 1:17:50.374
the peak of how good it was and how it ended.

1:17:50.416 --> 1:17:52.585
That's all we're taking into account,

1:17:52.627 --> 1:17:54.878
which is kind of amazing.

1:17:54.920 --> 1:17:57.214
It means that the movie has to end really well.

1:17:57.256 --> 1:17:59.925
So, I'm glad I get to be the last scientist.

1:18:01.636 --> 1:18:03.762
We're here in Puerto Rico,

1:18:03.804 --> 1:18:06.056
and in a few minutes, we're going to be going to

1:18:06.098 --> 1:18:08.601
an even smaller island in the Caribbean,

1:18:08.643 --> 1:18:10.645
which is an island that's just off the coast of Puerto Rico

1:18:10.686 --> 1:18:12.229
called Cayo Santiago.

1:18:12.271 --> 1:18:16.733
It's home to about 1,000 free-ranging monkeys.

1:18:16.775 --> 1:18:18.694
Glasses fog up.

1:18:18.735 --> 1:18:21.030
[gasps] Puppy!

1:18:21.071 --> 1:18:23.491
I know! I know you don't these folks.

1:18:25.909 --> 1:18:27.744
You want non-shiny glasses.

1:18:27.786 --> 1:18:29.288
Non-shiny? So not these ones.

1:18:29.330 --> 1:18:30.914
Yeah, they won't like that.

1:18:30.956 --> 1:18:33.334
See? That's good advice. Yeah, I didn't...

1:18:33.376 --> 1:18:35.419
They'll see themselves, and it'll be very threatening.

1:18:35.461 --> 1:18:36.920
Ah, okay.

1:18:40.174 --> 1:18:41.300
<i>Hola!</i>

1:18:41.342 --> 1:18:43.010
It's prettier than the lab.

1:18:43.052 --> 1:18:46.180
-This is a lot prettier. -It's an early wake-up call,

1:18:46.222 --> 1:18:48.140
but it's really beautiful and you get to enjoy it.

1:18:48.182 --> 1:18:50.560
[Anil] It's fantastic.

1:18:55.147 --> 1:18:59.776
First question: What is the main motivation

1:18:55.147 --> 1:18:59.776
for your research out here?

1:18:59.818 --> 1:19:02.238
So, I... I am a psychologist,

1:19:02.279 --> 1:19:04.240
a cognitive psychologist by training,

1:19:04.281 --> 1:19:06.158
which means, I'm kind of interested in how humans think.

1:19:06.200 --> 1:19:08.952
But I find it's really hard to test humans

1:19:08.994 --> 1:19:10.663
by testing humans.

1:19:10.705 --> 1:19:12.873
We have culture, we teach it.

1:19:12.915 --> 1:19:14.958
To get, to kind of get down to human cognition

1:19:15.000 --> 1:19:16.586
without all the extra stuff is hard.

1:19:16.627 --> 1:19:18.879
And the beauty of the monkeys, as you'll see,

1:19:18.921 --> 1:19:21.173
is they're just being monkeys.

1:19:27.263 --> 1:19:28.681
You guys into Pokemon Go?

1:19:28.723 --> 1:19:30.140
There's really good Pokemon on the docks.

1:19:30.182 --> 1:19:32.226
I always try to catch the Pokemon.

1:19:32.268 --> 1:19:35.020
No one can get these 'cause they're here.

1:19:35.062 --> 1:19:36.897
However we're walking around the island,

1:19:36.939 --> 1:19:38.941
find a path that's, like,

1:19:38.982 --> 1:19:41.110
furthest from all monkeys.

1:19:41.151 --> 1:19:43.446
Staring at them right in the face is like a threat.

1:19:43.487 --> 1:19:45.656
If they get upset with you, you'll know about it.

1:19:45.698 --> 1:19:47.491
They'll start threatening you like, "Ah!"

1:19:47.533 --> 1:19:49.201
How close is this to

1:19:49.243 --> 1:19:51.495
the natural habitat they might have come from?

1:19:51.537 --> 1:19:54.123
Macaques are the most

1:19:54.164 --> 1:19:56.417
ubiquitous primate, other than humans.

1:19:56.459 --> 1:19:58.461
The lore is they treat us like walking trees.

1:19:58.502 --> 1:20:00.713
If we almost stepped on them, they would move.

1:20:00.755 --> 1:20:03.382
But we're just kind of part of their environment.

1:20:03.424 --> 1:20:06.469
We're a slightly bigger group with the camera

1:20:06.510 --> 1:20:09.430
than we normally would be, so some of them are like, "What?"

1:20:11.307 --> 1:20:13.643
Our group does cognition work down here,

1:20:13.684 --> 1:20:16.646
which means we're really setting up experiments.

1:20:16.687 --> 1:20:19.148
We have to kind of stay in a compact spot

1:20:19.189 --> 1:20:20.899
so we're not interfering with data.

1:20:25.279 --> 1:20:27.615
We're going to also get a little poolside show.

1:20:27.657 --> 1:20:29.742
Those are a bunch of kid monkeys.

1:20:29.784 --> 1:20:32.035
Who's gonna go for it?

1:20:32.077 --> 1:20:33.870
-Psych yourself up. -Great!

1:20:35.122 --> 1:20:37.708
But, it's... It's so high, right?

1:20:37.750 --> 1:20:40.753
[Anil] So they... are they having fun?

1:20:40.795 --> 1:20:42.755
[Laurie] Yeah, this is playing.

1:20:49.094 --> 1:20:50.929
Maybe, do you think the female on the rock?

1:20:50.971 --> 1:20:52.515
-I was looking at her, yeah. -Yeah.

1:20:52.556 --> 1:20:55.100
So what we're going to do is,

1:20:55.142 --> 1:20:58.521
we're going show the monkeys a little show about what,

1:20:58.562 --> 1:21:01.440
what information Casey has about where an object is.

1:21:01.482 --> 1:21:03.734
So this one, she's going to do is the boring one.

1:21:03.776 --> 1:21:05.778
So, this is one that

1:21:05.820 --> 1:21:08.238
the monkeys shouldn't look for a very long time at all.

1:21:08.280 --> 1:21:10.324
They see her, watch it go into that box...

1:21:10.366 --> 1:21:12.075
and she reaches for it there.

1:21:12.117 --> 1:21:15.788
What we're looking for is long they watch that.

1:21:15.830 --> 1:21:17.956
You can see Shireen is behind her and she's filming

1:21:17.998 --> 1:21:20.250
how long they watch it.

1:21:20.292 --> 1:21:24.004
The expectation is the monkeys should lose interest

1:21:20.292 --> 1:21:24.004
more quickly.

1:21:24.046 --> 1:21:26.923
Is this something that works in controlled conditions,

1:21:26.965 --> 1:21:28.676
that monkeys can do, or...

1:21:28.718 --> 1:21:30.219
I think it would work under controlled conditions.

1:21:30.260 --> 1:21:31.970
But, you don't often in captivity have

1:21:32.012 --> 1:21:34.431
big enough sample sizes to do it.

1:21:34.473 --> 1:21:37.476
So, now the monkey is going to have a different belief

1:21:34.473 --> 1:21:37.476
than Casey.

1:21:37.518 --> 1:21:40.312
They see Casey watch it go into one spot,

1:21:40.354 --> 1:21:43.148
but then when Casey's not paying attention,

1:21:43.190 --> 1:21:45.275
the monkey can see a switch.

1:21:45.317 --> 1:21:47.236
Now...

1:21:47.277 --> 1:21:49.238
You can see this monkey doesn't seem to fine anymore.

1:21:49.279 --> 1:21:52.032
He's looking for a long time because it's unexpected.

1:21:54.076 --> 1:21:55.828
We're interested in whether the monkeys know

1:21:55.870 --> 1:21:59.498
that somebody has a different perspective than they do.

1:21:59.540 --> 1:22:02.042
We're expecting other minds

1:22:02.084 --> 1:22:03.878
to do these kind of jumps

1:22:03.919 --> 1:22:05.921
that our own minds do.

1:22:05.962 --> 1:22:08.632
It's not clear if they do the same thing.

1:22:11.802 --> 1:22:14.346
There's been this real question about whether another animal

1:22:14.388 --> 1:22:16.724
can think about what somebody else is thinking.

1:22:16.766 --> 1:22:19.435
Can they think about what somebody else sees?

1:22:21.186 --> 1:22:24.231
If monkeys know what other individuals see,

1:22:24.273 --> 1:22:27.276
they should use that information in productive ways.

1:22:27.317 --> 1:22:30.529
One productive way is in the concept of deception.

1:22:33.365 --> 1:22:37.202
We've got to find a nail or a stick.

1:22:37.244 --> 1:22:40.163
Most of monkey science happens with duct tape...

1:22:40.205 --> 1:22:41.832
and foam board.

1:22:44.501 --> 1:22:45.878
What are you making?

1:22:45.920 --> 1:22:47.337
We're going to make a little platform

1:22:47.379 --> 1:22:49.089
for them to steal grapes off of.

1:22:51.759 --> 1:22:54.637
We give them the opportunity to steal stuff from humans.

1:22:54.678 --> 1:22:57.055
The question is, do the monkeys steal more

1:22:57.097 --> 1:22:59.266
when folks aren't paying attention?

1:23:02.269 --> 1:23:04.939
This experiment is a first pass to see,

1:23:04.980 --> 1:23:08.108
can they use any of the social abilities they have

1:23:08.150 --> 1:23:09.735
to deceive us?

1:23:09.777 --> 1:23:11.445
Are they sensitive to this simple thing

1:23:11.487 --> 1:23:13.906
of what we can see, and what we can't see?

1:23:13.948 --> 1:23:17.075
Take one step towards them, like this.

1:23:17.117 --> 1:23:19.829
Then now, hold your platform horizontal, like this

1:23:19.870 --> 1:23:21.664
and show him the grape.

1:23:21.705 --> 1:23:25.125
Then place the grape down onto the shish kebab.

1:23:25.167 --> 1:23:27.002
Good.

1:23:27.043 --> 1:23:28.963
Now we're going to put the platform on the-- Hey! Wait!

1:23:29.004 --> 1:23:31.214
No, buddy. You've got to wait.

1:23:31.256 --> 1:23:33.717
Step back. Take your grape off.

1:23:33.759 --> 1:23:35.678
Yeah, he's very forceful.

1:23:35.719 --> 1:23:37.930
Nope, now you don't get to play 'cause you're being mean.

1:23:37.972 --> 1:23:40.474
We could try again but let's do it from slightly further back

1:23:40.516 --> 1:23:42.392
-So, we'll do it even from here. -Okay.

1:23:42.434 --> 1:23:44.520
Hey... Monkey!

1:23:46.313 --> 1:23:47.815
Okay, turn around.

1:23:50.484 --> 1:23:52.402
All right, he's...

1:23:52.444 --> 1:23:54.738
-I have no idea what's going on. -One sec.

1:23:54.780 --> 1:23:57.282
-You can turn around and grab the grape.

1:23:54.780 --> 1:23:57.282
-I can turn around?

1:23:57.324 --> 1:23:59.785
And turn around.

1:24:00.911 --> 1:24:03.330
Anything happening?

1:24:03.372 --> 1:24:05.666
They're staring at the film crew a little bit.

1:24:06.917 --> 1:24:09.670
Now he's threatening the film crew again.

1:24:09.712 --> 1:24:11.672
I'm trying to just stare off into the distance

1:24:11.714 --> 1:24:14.466
and pretend I'm not paying attention.

1:24:14.508 --> 1:24:17.052
What's fascinating here, is we just tried this experiment

1:24:17.093 --> 1:24:19.013
and it didn't really quite work.

1:24:19.054 --> 1:24:20.764
Typically, when we run these studies

1:24:20.806 --> 1:24:22.683
it's just two people, two grapes.

1:24:22.725 --> 1:24:24.309
No one else is around.

1:24:24.351 --> 1:24:26.979
Quite a large camera crew hanging around too...

1:24:27.021 --> 1:24:29.565
[Laurie] It fits with our hypothesis, right?

1:24:29.606 --> 1:24:31.316
The hypothesis of, monkeys see people are paying attention,

1:24:31.358 --> 1:24:34.361
they just hold back, they don't steal from anyone.

1:24:34.403 --> 1:24:38.198
And there's a lot of people here paying attention.

1:24:38.240 --> 1:24:40.158
They're very worried about the surveillance

1:24:40.200 --> 1:24:42.578
that you guys started on their core island.

1:24:44.038 --> 1:24:45.956
[Laurie] Whatever we do down here, it's nice if

1:24:45.998 --> 1:24:48.584
other folks are doing similar work in other places,

1:24:48.625 --> 1:24:52.629
so we can triangulate what the animals really understand.

1:24:52.671 --> 1:24:54.840
Even when we find things that don't work,

1:24:54.882 --> 1:24:57.384
we replicate it, we try it again.

1:24:57.426 --> 1:24:59.636
Part of our task is to put the pattern together

1:24:59.678 --> 1:25:03.515
of what works and what doesn't.

1:25:03.557 --> 1:25:06.476
To be a scientist, you have to deal with uncertainty

1:25:03.557 --> 1:25:06.476
all the time.

1:25:07.937 --> 1:25:10.564
But you're just thinking about other possibilities

1:25:10.606 --> 1:25:12.441
in general.

1:25:12.482 --> 1:25:14.944
What if the world was this way?

1:25:14.985 --> 1:25:18.488
Science is all about holding multiple things in mind.

1:25:18.530 --> 1:25:21.491
And ultimately it's probably using

1:25:21.533 --> 1:25:23.619
these very same rudimentary capacities

1:25:23.660 --> 1:25:26.162
that we're seeing in the monkeys.

1:25:27.372 --> 1:25:29.458
Getting outside your own head

1:25:29.499 --> 1:25:32.878
is a lot of what science is about.

1:25:32.920 --> 1:25:35.881
That's what we're trying to do with the brains we have,

1:25:35.923 --> 1:25:39.175
to understand our place in the universe.

1:26:13.251 --> 1:26:15.587
You might think, watching scientists,

1:26:15.629 --> 1:26:18.132
that we go through a lot of frustrating things

1:26:18.173 --> 1:26:20.717
to do our science, like, why would we do it?

1:26:22.803 --> 1:26:24.805
Functionally, what scientists are doing is that

1:26:24.847 --> 1:26:27.223
we're trying to solve a really long mystery novel

1:26:27.265 --> 1:26:28.684
all the time.

1:26:28.725 --> 1:26:30.060
We get to the end of the chapter,

1:26:30.102 --> 1:26:31.687
and we think we've made progress.

1:26:31.728 --> 1:26:34.148
but then there's a new door and a new twist!

1:26:34.189 --> 1:26:36.817
For us, that's fun, that there's more to go.

1:26:38.568 --> 1:26:39.987
Are you Jen?

1:26:40.029 --> 1:26:42.031
-Hi, I'm Jen! -It's good to meet you.

1:26:42.072 --> 1:26:43.740
I'm going to give you a hug. I feel like I know you already.

1:26:43.782 --> 1:26:45.742
I can't believe you made it here before I did.

1:26:45.784 --> 1:26:48.162
I was so excited about the caves, I couldn't help myself.

1:26:50.205 --> 1:26:51.623
So, let's see...

1:26:51.665 --> 1:26:53.125
Suit.

1:26:57.713 --> 1:26:59.756
All right, I've got to figure out how this hat works.

1:26:59.798 --> 1:27:01.383
Is it, like...

1:27:01.424 --> 1:27:03.177
See, there's a...

1:27:03.218 --> 1:27:05.179
-a little button there. -Oh, yeah.

1:27:07.222 --> 1:27:08.849
I think you gave me a broken one.

1:27:10.809 --> 1:27:13.436
One thing I feel at a gut level

1:27:13.478 --> 1:27:15.271
is that humans get smarter,

1:27:15.313 --> 1:27:17.566
the more different things they experience.

1:27:20.777 --> 1:27:23.197
We can't possibly imagine the things that

1:27:23.238 --> 1:27:26.491
we might learn, that might be useful to us.

1:27:27.784 --> 1:27:31.788
We're slowly creeping towards understanding.

1:27:31.830 --> 1:27:34.499
But we're... We're sort of toward the beginning.
